<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / EU and UN streamline humanitarian aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Union signed an agreement with the United Nations yesterday to
streamline humanitarian aid operations and approved about Dollars 130m
(Pounds 87.2m) in aid, most of it for ex-Yugoslavia, AP reports from
Brussels.
'The agreement is an important step forward,' said Mrs Sadako Ogata, the UN
High Commissioner for Refugees. It would allow the two organisations to
avoid costly overlap and speed up operations.
On Monday, the European Commission approved Ecu59m (Pounds 45m) in emergency
aid for Bosnia, which will be spent in co-ordination with the UNHCR. The
Commission also approved aid to the other republics, bringing overall aid to
Ecu86m.
David Gardner adds: According to EU diplomats in Brussels, a number of
foreign ministers from the 12 member states were last night and today due to
go to different parts of ex-Yugoslavia to prepare the ground for peace talks
planned for Brussels on December 22.
The diplomats said the decision was taken at yesterday's EU foreign
ministers' meeting in Brussels. They said Germany had floated the idea at
last weekend's EU heads of government summit of using the influence that
different member states had with contenders in the Bosnian war to try to
achieve peace terms.
The EU insists Serbia give up a portion of the land that it has conquered in
Bosnia.
Diplomats said it was likely the Netherlands would send its foreign minister
to Sarajevo, that Bonn would send its foreign minister to Zagreb - where
Germany wields influence  - and that several foreign ministers would
intercede with Belgrade.
Among the latter group Greece and possibly the UK and France were likely to
send representatives.
</TEXT>
