<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Search for allies steps up in Italy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The populist Northern League led by Mr Umberto Bossi has decided to break
out of its political isolation and work for a 'liberal-democrat' alliance
that includes Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the media magnate.
This is the main upshot of a League congress at the weekend during which Mr
Bossi imposed his full authority.
In the run-up to the congress, Mr Bossi had been criticised both for his
autocratic leadership style and for failing to see the need for alliances in
the recent local elections. The League, the party winning most votes in the
north, campaigned alone and lacked support to win vital mayoral seats in the
biggest cities of Genoa, Trieste and Venice.
The Italian media have been speculating on a link-up between the League and
Mr Berlusconi's nascent political ambitions for several months, but the
matter has now been taken one stage further. Over the weekend Mr Berlusconi
was perfectly happy to let his name be linked openly to the League in what
appeared a well orchestrated initiative.
Mr Bossi admitted the League had to change tactics to ensure it maintained a
voice in Italy's fast changing political scene. He proposed the League as
the hard core of an electoral alliance to fight the progressive one formed
to good effect at the local level by the former communist Party of the
Democratic Left (PDS) to contest the municipal elections of November 21 and
December 6.
'In Mr Bossi's speech (to the congress), I found significant overtures
towards the idea of a broad liberal-democrat alliance,' Mr Berlusconi was
quoted as saying. 'I hope we can come close enough to form a coalition
capable of representing a majority in the country and blocking the PDS's
conquest of power.'
Mr Berlusconi's supporters indicated the League's federalist ideas were a
potential source of friction. The League congress called for reform of
Italy's constitution to introduce a federal structure dividing Italy into
three - Padania (north of the river Po), Etrurira (the centre) and the
south.
More importantly Mr Berlusconi could put his TV network licence agreements
at risk by active involvement in politics. In the past three weeks he has
used his networks, which control more than 80 per cent of Italy's commercial
TV, for self-promotion that goes against the spirit of the licences.
Mr Berlusconi's political judgment has already been exposed with his
under-estimation of the consequences of associating himself last month with
Mr Gianfranco Fini, leader of the neo-fascist MSI.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
