<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 93 / Building review attacks abuses and lack of trust
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Guidelines aimed at reducing contract abuses and litigation in the Pounds
45bn-a-year construction industry will be published today as the first stage
in a wide-ranging review of business practices in the sector.
The review, jointly financed by construction employers and the Department of
the Environment, is thought to be highly critical of adversarial attitudes
between companies and clients which it says have soured commercial
relationships and have damaged the industry's reputation.
The interim report by Sir Michael Latham, the former Conservative MP and
ex-director of the Housebuilders' Federation who led the review, is
understood to refer to a climate of deep mistrust and a disturbing
atmosphere which had led to considerable dissatisfaction in the industry.
The guidelines are designed to improve ways in which property developers and
other private-sector and public-sector customers award contracts and make
payments to construction companies.
A second, more detailed report due to published next summer will examine
ways in which contractors and others working in the building industry can
improve practices and reduce friction in commercial relationships.
DoE officials believe the chances that the review's recommendations will be
implemented are boosted by the broad support it has received. It has been
supported by construction industry leaders as well as representatives of
some of its most important customers including property companies, local
authorities, banks and large industrial companies.
Sir Michael's interim report is expected to recommend that customers seeking
better value should consider reducing the size of tender lists. In one
instance the review body was told that a local authority had sought bids
from 28 companies for a heating and ventilation contract worth less than
Pounds 250,000.
This size of competition for small or medium-size contracts is wasteful when
the customer must have known that many of those asked to bid had very little
chance of success. Companies required to spend large sums pursuing
unnecessary bids will try to recover this expenditure on jobs they do win,
the report is understood to conclude.
It is also expected to criticise customers who drive prices down to
uneconomic levels in the belief that they are getting the best value. It
warns that contractors faced with a loss may try to cut corners.
Construction companies may also seek to recoup losses by overcharging
clients for late design changes.
The report is also understood to criticise customers who delay payments and
thereby put contractors and sub-contractors at risk.
A report by Construction Intelligence Data, an independent research and
credit rating organisation, warned earlier this year that 60 per cent of all
construction contracts were paid late.
</TEXT>
