<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 93 / Pressure for Bank autonomy grows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government will come under pressure this week to cede greater
independence to the Bank of England.
The all-party Commons Treasury committee is expected to call for a degree of
autonomy that would bring the Bank more into line with the New Zealand
model, under which the government cannot directly determine the Reserve
Bank's monetary policy.
Its report, to be published on Thursday, will coincide with the publication
of a private member's bill by one of its members, Tory MP Mr Nicholas
Budgen, as part of his drive for greater Bank of England transparency.
Mr Budgen, a leading Euro-rebel, said: 'The problem at the moment is that
monetary policy can be changed without anyone knowing what is happening.'
Mr Budgen argues that publication of monetary policy guidelines would give
the Commons more, not less, control over the Bank.
In New Zealand the government has a contract with the central bank
specifying a target inflation range. Failure to achieve this can result in
dismissal of the governor.
Sir Robin Butler, the UK cabinet secretary, is to visit New Zealand next
month and is expected to examine the workings of the Reserve Bank.
Although Mr Budgen's bill has little chance of becoming law, it will add to
the debate on the issue. It is due for a second reading on January 28.
The Treasury committee is understood to have rejected independence as in
Germany's Bundesbank, largely because it operates under such a different
political system. The New Zealand system, however, is similar to that of the
UK. While the committee's report stops short of recommending the New Zealand
model, it favours giving the Bank autonomy.
</TEXT>
