<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 93 / MoD trains its big guns on commercial target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
By any international standards, Britain's Ministry of Defence has already
gone a long way down the road to privatisation and commercial management.
But while senior defence officials are convinced that market-testing will
bring significant savings, the benefits so far are hard to evaluate.
Ten years ago the MoD made its own ammunition and refitted its own ships.
But since 1987 the Royal Ordnance munitions factories have been part of
British Aerospace. The dockyards have been under commercial management and
are now to be sold. In April this year the 6,800 employees at the Atomic
Weapons Establishment, which makes nuclear warheads, left the civil service
when Hunting-Brae, a private consortium, took over full managerial
responsibility.
In all these areas, the workload from the MoD has fallen drastically. The
government wants to keep both the Devonport and Rosyth dockyards, and plans
soon to invite separate tenders for their privatisation. But top navy
officers have argued that a single dockyard, working to capacity, could be
tens of millions of pounds a year more efficient.
The Commons public accounts committee earlier this year found that
uncertainty and falls in workload 'made it difficult for the commercial
managers to operate on a fully commercial basis and improve efficiency', but
costs had been cut (the two dockyards, like Royal Ordnance, have cut
workforces by two-thirds in 10 years).
Recent contracts include the MoD's computer services centre, now run by
Hoskyns, the information-technology company. The initial stages of RAF and
Navy flying training, at Topcliffe in North Yorkshire, have been contracted
out to Hunting. The Army Base Repair Organisation, which repairs army
fighting vehicles is being market-tested.
The National Audit Office recently estimated that savings from
private-sector competition averaged 24 per cent, or Pounds 64m a year. It
said the policy had cut 17,300 posts since 1979.
Defence activities figure strongly among the government executive agencies
currently being reviewed.
The MoD's experience with private contractors has not all been good,
however. It recently cancelled a contract with a company, Airwork, which it
blamed for causing damage 'of a very serious nature' to Tornado fighters
which it was modifying. And when the NAO asked the opinion of MoD officials
monitoring cleaning contracts, it found that only a third considered the
ministry was getting value for money.
</TEXT>
