<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 93 / Hungary mourns death of premier Antall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jozsef Antall, Hungary's conservative prime minister and eastern Europe's
longest- serving leader, died yesterday afternoon at the age of 61, after
heart trouble compounded his cancer condition.
His death, after 3 1/2 years in office, follows a long battle against
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a form of cancer with which the prime minister was
diagnosed in 1990, the year he and his centre-right coalition were elected.
The demise of Mr Antall, leader of the governing Hungarian Democratic Forum,
threatens political turbulence, coming shortly before elections pencilled in
for next May,
Taking over as interim prime minister is Mr Peter Boross, the interior
minister, who deputised for Mr Antall during his hospital treatment.
But the succession is by no means certain and other candidates such as
defence minister Lajos Fur may emerge. The struggle is set to shift the
centre of political gravity within the Forum to the right as contenders seek
the support of party activists. A potential kingmaker is Mr Sandor Lezsak,
who runs the day-to-day affairs of the Forum and has publicly played down
his desire to do the job himself.
Last night he said on Hungarian television: 'The HDF's leading bodies are
determined not to have a struggle for succession so that the country can
maintain its creative calm and security without which, I believe, we cannot
have firm prospects for the future.'
A possible alternative to the election by MPs of a new prime minister is
that the parliament dissolves itself and Mr Arpad Goncz, the president,
calls early elections.
Mr Antall's death is a loss for the Forum because, though his popularity
ratings were low, he was widely respected, even by his opponents, and seen
as an electoral asset.
Thousands of mourners gathered in front of Budapest's ornate parliament
building last night to sing Hungary's national anthem and light candles in
Mr Antall's memory as the caretaker cabinet met in emergency session.
Ministers, Mr Goncz and leaders of the Democratic Forum party later emerged
to join the throng.
Mr Antall's departure from the political scene depresses the Forum's chances
of staging a recovery in public support from the 10 per cent recorded in the
latest opinion polls. The Forum now faces an uphill battle against a
resurgent Hungarian Socialist Party, the former communists, as well as a
liberal bloc.
The change in leadership will raise concerns about the country's reputation
as an island of stability in an unsettled region, an achievement tied to Mr
Antall's personality.
Nevertheless all the potential successors to Mr Antall share a commitment to
the market economy and Hungary's integration into the western community.
</TEXT>
