<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 93 / US and EU edge nearer deal on trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A seesaw session of world trade talks that started in a mood of crisis ended
early today with the US and EU apparently having settled wide-ranging
disagreements which were jeopardising a successful outcome of the Uruguay
Round.
Most critically, dispute over US hopes to dilute anti-dumping rules have
been settled, with officials of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
saying 95 per cent of the Uruguay Round text had now been agreed.
The US and EU have still failed, however, to reach agreement on opening
Europe's markets for television and films. Other important areas such as
financial services and shipping continue to leave the important services
sector in the balance. Intellectual property rights and a successor to the
US-EU aircraft code were also unresolved.
Mr Peter Sutherland, director general of Gatt, said after talks broke up
that the session had been an 'amazing success' and that the treaty text was
almost complete.
The progress came after Sir Leon Brittan, the chief EU negotiator, cancelled
plans to return to Brussels on Sunday evening. He and other senior trade
officials continued talks with their US counterparts at the EU's trade
mission in Geneva until the early hours.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, who was to hold a breakfast
meeting today with Sir Leon, said: 'We've made tremendous progress.' He said
that beside the audio-visual dispute, the farm trade issue was still open.
A Gatt official said the aim now was to complete texts for an overall
agreement by late today. This, he added, depends on the US and EU wrapping
up their differences.
He said the Gatt secretariat hoped to distribute the texts to heads of
delegations late in the day. The Trade Negotiations Committee, which
oversees the Uruguay Round talks, will hold a meeting tomorrow.
Earlier yesterday, before talks resumed in the evening, Mr Sutherland
accused the US and EU of blocking progress.
His accusations came as US President Bill Clinton telephoned French Prime
Minister Edouard Balladur, British Prime Minister John Major and German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl in an effort to rescue the talks.
The discussions, which began with a breakfast-time disclosure by Sir Leon
that the talks were 'in crisis', involved nerve-racking brinkmanship that
appeared to leave successful outcome of the trade talks by the December 15
deadline in the balance.
While speculation spread that negotiators were examining exclusion of
financial services from the negotiations, later comments confirmed that the
US-EU dispute over access to Europe's television and film markets was the
key stumbling block.
At the EU summit in Brussels, which ended on Saturday, Mr Ruud Lubbers,
Dutch prime minister, said it might be necessary to 'stop the clock' on the
Wednesday midnight deadline for concluding the Uruguay Round. That followed
adoption of a hardened EU position on audiovisual trade, textiles and
demands by France and several other member states for tougher trade weapons.
But Mr Sutherland dismissed the possibility of changing the deadline as 'a
misapprehension of the highest order'.
French officials believe the summit guidelines to EU negotiators to secure
special, separate treatment for European cinema and broadcasting should be
sufficient for the French government to get a Gatt deal through the National
Assembly this week.
Gatt reports, Pages 3 and 4
Last hurrah, Page 27
