<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 93 / Yeltsin claims referendum win
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Russian voters have approved plans for a reformed constitution that would
give strong powers to Mr Boris Yeltsin, the president's advisers said last
night.
However, the elections for the Russian parliament showed fragile support for
radical reform. The Communist party and the neo-fascist Liberal Democratic
party of Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky were the main beneficiaries of a low
turnout.
With Russia seemingly poised between reform and reaction, Mr Yegor Gaidar,
first deputy prime minister and leader of the liberal Russia's Choice group,
said the 'possible success of the extremists is a result of the new social
and economic situation in the country, and also because of divisions on the
part of the democrats'. Mr Anatoly Chubais, the deputy prime minister for
privatisation, appealed to the democrats to 'unite in the face of a new
fascist threat'.
Although the turnout nationwide was low, it was enough to pass the 50 per
cent barrier needed for the vote on the constitution to be valid. Mr
Vladimir Shumeiko, first deputy prime minister, said that about 60 per cent
of those voting had backed the new constitution - an outcome which, he said,
gave the government stable conditions for its work.
Early indications of results gave a mixed picture of the parties' positions,
although all showed a considerable strength for the Communists and the
Liberal Democrats.
Germany's ARD public television news reported an exit poll carried out by
Russian polling institutes as showing that 23 per cent had voted for
Russia's Choice, 17 per cent for the Communists and 13 per cent for the
Liberal Democrats.
However, results for four constituencies broadcast by the Ostankino TV
company put the Liberal Democrats on 24 per cent, the Communists on 17,
Russia's Choice on 16.1 per cent and the conservative Agrarian Party on 8.3.
Further figures from the far-eastern Primorsky district, which includes the
city of Vladivostok, put Russia's Choice on 17 per cent, the Liberal
Democrats on 14 per cent, the Communists on 13 per cent and the Yabloko
group of Mr Grigory Yavlinsky on 11 per cent.
While detailed results will not be available until today or tomorrow, it is
clear that the new parliament, set to convene on January 11, will contain a
solid block of strongly nationalist deputies dedicated to opposing
pro-market reforms and to promoting anti-western policies.
Mr Gennady Burbulis, a leader of Russia's Choice and a former close aide to
President Yeltsin, blamed his former boss for refusing to support Russia's
Choice and preferring to stay above the conflict. 'We will now have to
swallow our pride and seek concrete compromises,' he told the Interfax news
agency.
Mr Vyacheslav Kostikov, the president's spokesman, said it might be possible
to co-operate with communist and nationalist parties.
Both the capital, Moscow, and the second city, St Petersburg, registered a
bare majority of participating voters, while the big city of Ekaterinburg,
home town of President Yeltsin, failed to register 50 per cent - as did
several other important regions.
As expected, the north Caucasian republic of Chechnya took no part in the
elections.
RUSSIAN ELECTIONS
