<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 93 / Yorkshire TV group to defer results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yorkshire-Tyne Tees Television will announce today that it is deferring
publication of its financial results until the end of January and passing
its final dividend.
The company had always said it would announce its results for the year to
September tomorrow.
Last month the north-east ITV company warned that a loss was likely for the
1992-93 year because of unexpected problems on advertising sales, through
overtrading - selling more air time than it had available - and pulling
advertising revenue forward by offering heavy discounts.
The company will promise today that pre-tax losses for the year are unlikely
to exceed Pounds 9.5m. The final figures may be up to Pounds 1m lower.
Meanwhile the Yorkshire board has given permission for LWT to explore in
detail an agreed bid to take over Yorkshire. As part of the proposals Anglia
Television would buy Tyne Tees. The deal is designed to fend off a hostile
bid from the Granada group for LWT.
The Yorkshire-Tyne Tees announcement will come on the day that the House of
Lords debates government proposals which will allow one company to hold two
broadcasting licences. LWT hopes government liberalisation of ownership
rules will allow LWT, Yorkshire, Tyne Tees and Anglia to join together to
form the largest ITV grouping.
Mr Gerry Robinson, chief executive of Granada, the television rental and
leisure group, is pushing ahead with his takeover bid for LWT. Mr Robinson
said yesterday: 'Granada and LWT make a perfect fit.'
Central Television shareholders will today receive the details of the
Carlton Communications offer which values Central, the second largest ITV
company, at Pounds 814m, equal to Pounds 27.92 for each Central ordinary
share.
